==English==

===Etymology===
Derived from Old French "cucuault" (from "cucu," the Cuckoo bird, some varieties of which lay their eggs in another's nest).  Appears in Middle English in noun form circa 1250 as "cokewald."  First known use of the verb form is 1589.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|cuckold|cuckolds}}
# A [[man]] [[married]] to an [[unfaithful]] [[wife]] (latterly one who condones or tolerates her unfaithfulness).
# A comic figure from medieval and Shakespearian drama.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|cuckold|cuckolds|cuckolded|cuckolding}}
#{{transitive}} To make a cuckold of someone by being unfaithful.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|cuckoldly}}
# Possessing the qualities of a cuckold.

===Examples===
William Shakespeare:

:Now, sir, who's a cuckold now?
:—Merry Wives of Windsor: V, v
 
:I will chop her into messes: cuckold me!
:—Othello: IV, i

:Use her as the key of the cuckoldly rogue's coffer
:—Merry Wives of Windsor: II, ii 


